Robert Pomeroy, Jr.
Partner

6380 South Fiddlers Green Circle, Suite 500, Greenwood Village, CO 80111P 303.290.1622


Download as PDF
Download vCard
Send Email












OVERVIEW
Bob Pomeroy has saved his electric consumer clients hundreds of millions of dollars in power costs during a career spanning 40 years.

Having counseled the largest and most well-established coalitions of electric consumers and independent power producers in the Mountain West, Bob understands the challenges electric consumers face today in a rapidly changing regulatory environment, and his work also has helped open wholesale and retail electric markets in the West to new competitive business opportunities for independent power producers.
Bob has won energy and public utilities cases for his electricity clients in the Colorado and Wyoming Supreme Courts and other state and federal courts.  He also appears before the public utilities commissions in Colorado, Wyoming, Utah, Montana, New Mexico and Idaho.




EXPERIENCEExperienceRepresented clients in energy project development and the purchase or sale of electricity, assisting them on:

Contract negotiations
Rate proceedings
Regulatory issues
Electric transmission
Legislation and administrative agency issues arising out of the changing federal and state regulatory environment


Provides counsel and advocacy in administrative proceedings involving:

Rate cases
Tariff issues
Construction projects
Resource planning and transmission
Qualifying facilities
Mergers and acquisitions
Service quality matters
Line extensions
Legislation
Environmental regulatory requirement
Demand side management



CLIENT RESULTS

Client Results

Represented a client coalition in a first-of-its-kind proceeding before a state utilities commission involving an electric utility’s proposed addition of expensive air quality controls for one of its aging coal-fired power plants.  The electric utility initially proposed to spend over $250 Million for the air quality control equipment, but an investigation by Holland & Hart and our team of expert witnesses into the cost-effectiveness of the utility’s proposal ultimately led to finding a dramatically less expensive alternative for our clients and all of the utility’s other ratepayers over a six-state region.  Due to its significantly lower cost, the alternative solution ultimately selected will save the utility’s consumers, including our client coalition, over $225 Million. 

Represented a coalition of industrial electric consumers before a state utility commission in opposing an “all-energy” rate design proposed by an electric utility that would have dramatically increased rates for larger consumers.  In appealing the initial ruling of the commission in favor of the utility, Mr. Pomeroy succeeded in having the unfavorable rate design overturned at both the state district court level and at the state Supreme Court, resulting in a major victory for his clients.

Represented a coalition of over 30 independent power producers– including both fossil fuel and renewable power plant developers – in opposing Public Service Company of Colorado's (PSCo) proposal before the Colorado Public Utilities Commission (PUC) for a complete exemption from Colorado's competitive bidding requirement for new power plants, which, if granted, would have eliminated any business opportunity in Colorado for non-utility power developers.  Although no other party resisted the PSCo request for an exemption from bidding, following three full weeks of contested hearings, the PUC ruled entirely in our client coalition's favor and required PSCo to compete with independent developers for new power plants.  The final order approved over 1,000 megawatts of new generation resources, all of which were to be built by independent power producers, providing several hundreds of millions of dollars in new business opportunities in Colorado to our clients.

Represented a major national wind developer in securing unanimous approval from the Colorado Public Utilities Commission of a 200MW wind farm in Eastern Colorado over the vigorous opposition of other parties to the case.  In that proceeding, approval of the wind farm was contested by the Staff of the Colorado Public Utilities Commission, industrial consumers, gas producers and other wind developers.  Mr. Pomeroy served as lead counsel for the developer of the wind farm, and developed and implemented a coordinated strategy with the local electric utility that secured the required Commission approval after a contested hearing.

Served as lead counsel for an industrial electric consumer client coalition in opposing a $91 Million rate increase triggered by volatile power markets at the time of the failure of a major power plant by an electric utility.  Following an investigation into the cause of the power plant failure and into the power purchasing practices of the utility, the Holland & Hart legal team secured a complete disallowance of the proposed rate increase, an outcome which was ultimately upheld by the state Supreme Court, saving his the members of his client coalition alone well over $40 Million in annual electricity costs.

Serves as lead counsel for a 22-member coalition of large electric consumers, the Wyoming Industrial Energy Consumers (WIEC), in electric regulatory proceedings before the Wyoming Public Service Commission, continuing a representation that began in 1994 when he was selected by WIEC as its Legal Counsel upon WIEC’s formation.  He has represented WIEC in every major electric rate case since that time.  For example, in 2011 and 2012 rate cases, the WIEC legal team succeeded in reducing the final rate hike for consumers by more than one-half, cutting back the 2011 rate increase from $98 Million to only $44 Million and 2012 rate increases from $92 Million to only $41 Million, resulting in annual total electric bill savings for our client coalition of over $25 Million in each year.

Spearheaded the formation of the largest and longest-running industrial electric consumer coalitions in Colorado, Montana and Wyoming and for decades, with other members of Holland & Hart, has represented those coalitions before their respective state public utilities commissions.  He has also served as lead counsel in the formation of independent power plant developer coalitions in New Mexico and Wyoming, while serving as lead counsel for a similar coalition in Colorado.  In addition, he has represented individual industrial electric consumers and individual independent power producers (both fossil fuels and renewable) in major electric regulatory proceedings and rate cases before state utilities commissions across the Mountain West.





